There is NOT a difference. A TRUE R5 is simply the region code. DVD's for sale in the retail region R5 means it was a real retail DVD made for sale in Russia and western europe. IT IS a REAL DVD. Why is it that R5's have great video, but when english is the spoken language, it is taken from a CAM and laid in sync (if the person doing this has a clue) over the Russian audio. No ones need argue with me about it, Google what R5 means in terms of movie releases on DVD and you will have millions of legit places that will explain to anyone that is interested in the truth. Don't hate the messenger. 
There also other region codes:  R2, R3, R4, R6 and other region codes. This code system makes it easy to make sure retail DVD's that are spoken in Greek for example, don't get shipped to Japan by mistake. 
Another example:
It would be a mess to get 400 cases of the DVD -LIMITLESS- that are dubbed by the studio into Chinese and they get sent to Peru. The region codes prevent this.  
R5 regions include area's in Russia. When it is Monday at 5pm here in Canada on the east coast, it is already Tuesday in a few places in Russia. Remember Russia covers like 10 or 11 time zones (almost half the surface of the planet. . . SO, a Russian uploading a DVD he bought on HIS Tuesday the way the time zones are figured, it will appear on TPB on our Monday. This makes it seem as if the R5 is an early release, but it isn't.  The difference in time zones is what makes it seem that way.  

As mentioned, the R5 designation is only a way to know what region it is supposed to be sold in. Some DVD players will NOT play DVD's with  a region code that isn't the same as the Region code of the DVD player itself. All this is old news. If there is any doubt, Wikipedia has an extensive explanation. It even has nice color coded maps of the whole world showing what region codes correspond to what countries. and it explains how the region codes in your DVD player can affect weather a given DVD will or will not play in your player. Some players are "REGION FREE" and will play any dvd no matter where it is from. You can even re-flash your computers DVD player with new firmware to allow it to play DVD's from regions it wasn't originally supposed to. (If you bought a used external DVD burner from EBAY for example, and it turns out it has a region code set different from where you live. If this was to happen, you would need to change or reset your DVD Player/Burner's region codes to match your area or set to "region free") I think a DVD player that is region R1 will play ANY DVD.

I would bet some are infact mis-labeled with the assumption of it being an R5. I really can't speak to that, I don't know why. This observation in no way de-bunks my previously posted comment/info on what a region code is. As B4, don't rag on or hate the messenger, I had to learn about this at one point as well. Knowledge is Power. There are MANY Many places the speak on the subject of R5 DVD's and all the other region codes.
